<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-09-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-09-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="131" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d131">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72111 Em 1/34½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-09-14">
                                    <hi rend="italic">September 14, 1915</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: Congratulations on your
                            Austrian arms note. It is a beautiful piece of work.</p>
                        <p>Enclosed tribute to your policy in a German paper may interest you.<note n="40" xml:id="d131fn1">Not printed.</note> It is written by a
                            friend of mine. (Not a German Viereck or Marcus Braun<note n="41" xml:id="d131fn2">Authors of periodical and newspaper articles
                                favorable to Germany.</note>).</p>
                        <p>Yours ever,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">James W. Gerard</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>